<tr><td></td><td>TEASER</td></tr>
<tr><td></td><td>LOCATION--Mine tunnel</td></tr>
<tr id="L1"><td><a href="#L1">1</a></td><td>ANNOTATION: A nervous man has his weapon drawn</td></tr>

<tr id="L2"><td><a href="#L2">2</a></td><td>SAM:  Who's there?</td></tr>

<tr id="L3"><td><a href="#L3">3</a></td><td>VANDERBERG:  (enters with a lot of men) It's your relief, Sam. All quiet?</td></tr>

<tr id="L4"><td><a href="#L4">4</a></td><td>SAM:  Didn't see a thing, Chief.</td></tr>

<tr id="L5"><td><a href="#L5">5</a></td><td>SCHMITTER:  Nobody ever does. Whatever the thing is, it's already killed fifty people. I never realised before how dark it is down here.</td></tr>

<tr id="L6"><td><a href="#L6">6</a></td><td>VANDERBERG:  Stay on your toes, Schmitter. Keep your phaser in your hand at all times.</td></tr>

<tr id="L7"><td><a href="#L7">7</a></td><td>SCHMITTER:  What good will that do? You saw what happened to Ed Appel when he shot at it. How about those other people before the monster got them?</td></tr>

<tr id="L8"><td><a href="#L8">8</a></td><td>VANDERBERG:  I'm sorry, Schmitter. I know how you feel, but we've got to have guards.</td></tr>

<tr id="L9"><td><a href="#L9">9</a></td><td>SCHMITTER:  Okay, Chief. I'll do what I can.</td></tr>

<tr id="L10"><td><a href="#L10">10</a></td><td>VANDERBERG:  Keep alert. If you hear anything or see anything, call in. Somebody can arrive in three minutes.</td></tr>

<tr id="L11"><td><a href="#L11">11</a></td><td>SCHMITTER:  A lot can happen in three minutes. Chief, is it true the Enterprise is on its way?</td></tr>

<tr id="L12"><td><a href="#L12">12</a></td><td>VANDERBERG:  It's coming.</td></tr>

<tr id="L13"><td><a href="#L13">13</a></td><td>SCHMITTER:  You think it could get here in the next four hours?</td></tr>

<tr id="L14"><td><a href="#L14">14</a></td><td>VANDERBERG:  You'll be all right.</td></tr>

<tr id="L15"><td><a href="#L15">15</a></td><td>ANNOTATION: The group leaves, and nervous Schmitter paces. Then we hear a scraping sound. He turns, looks and screams. Vanderberg and the others run back.</td></tr>

<tr id="L16"><td><a href="#L16">16</a></td><td>VANDERBERG:  Come on.</td></tr>

<tr id="L17"><td><a href="#L17">17</a></td><td>ANNOTATION: It's mere moments, but they're already too late.</td></tr>

<tr id="L18"><td><a href="#L18">18</a></td><td>VANDERBERG:  Schmitter. Like the rest of them. Burned to a crisp.</td></tr>

<tr id="L19"><td><a href="#L19">19</a></td><td>SOMEONE: Captain's log, stardate 3196.1. A distress call from the pergium production station on Janus Six has brought the Enterprise to that long-established colony. Mister Spock, Doctor McCoy, and I have beamed down to meet with Chief Engineer Vanderberg, administrative head of Janus Six.</td></tr>

<tr><td></td><td>LOCATION--Vanderberg's office</td></tr>
<tr id="L20"><td><a href="#L20">20</a></td><td>KIRK:  All right, let's assume there is a monster. What has it done? When did it start?</td></tr>

<tr id="L21"><td><a href="#L21">21</a></td><td>VANDERBERG:  About three months ago, we opened up a new level. Sensors gave us an unusually rich pergium reading. Not only pergium, whatever you want. Uranium, sirium, platinum. The whole planet's like that. It's a treasure house.</td></tr>

<tr id="L22"><td><a href="#L22">22</a></td><td>KIRK:  Yes, we're aware of that. If mining conditions weren't so difficult, Janus Six could supply the mineral needs of a thousand planets. But what happened?</td></tr>

<tr id="L23"><td><a href="#L23">23</a></td><td>VANDERBERG:  First, the automatic machinery, piece by piece, started to almost disintegrate. Metal began dissolving away. There was no reason for it, and our chemists were unable to analyse the corrosive agent.</td></tr>

<tr id="L24"><td><a href="#L24">24</a></td><td>SPOCK:  I'm sure there is an answer. It simply has not yet been discovered.</td></tr>

<tr id="L25"><td><a href="#L25">25</a></td><td>VANDERBERG:  Yes, it has. I don't know what this butchering monster is, but I know what it's doing. Our maintenance engineers sent down to the drifts to repair the corroded machinery. We found them seared to a crisp.</td></tr>

<tr id="L26"><td><a href="#L26">26</a></td><td>KIRK:  Volcanic activity?</td></tr>

<tr id="L27"><td><a href="#L27">27</a></td><td>SPOCK:  There is no current volcanic activity on this planet, Captain.</td></tr>

<tr id="L28"><td><a href="#L28">28</a></td><td>VANDERBERG:  He's right. None. At first the deaths were down deep, but they've been moving up toward our levels. The last man died two days ago three levels below this.</td></tr>

<tr id="L29"><td><a href="#L29">29</a></td><td>KIRK:  Same way? Burned?</td></tr>

<tr id="L30"><td><a href="#L30">30</a></td><td>MCCOY:  I'd like to examine the body.</td></tr>

<tr id="L31"><td><a href="#L31">31</a></td><td>VANDERBERG:  We kept it for you. There isn't much left. Roberts will show you. (McCoy and the guard leave) It isn't pretty.</td></tr>

<tr id="L32"><td><a href="#L32">32</a></td><td>KIRK:  Do you post sentries? Guards?</td></tr>

<tr id="L33"><td><a href="#L33">33</a></td><td>VANDERBERG:  Of course. Five of them have died.</td></tr>

<tr id="L34"><td><a href="#L34">34</a></td><td>KIRK:  Who else has seen this?</td></tr>

<tr id="L35"><td><a href="#L35">35</a></td><td>APPEL:  (entering) I have.</td></tr>

<tr id="L36"><td><a href="#L36">36</a></td><td>VANDERBERG:  This is Ed Appel, chief processing engineer.</td></tr>

<tr id="L37"><td><a href="#L37">37</a></td><td>KIRK:  Describe it.</td></tr>

<tr id="L38"><td><a href="#L38">38</a></td><td>APPEL:  I can't. I only got a glimpse of it, but it's big and shaggy.</td></tr>

<tr id="L39"><td><a href="#L39">39</a></td><td>VANDERBERG:  Ed shot it.</td></tr>

<tr id="L40"><td><a href="#L40">40</a></td><td>SPOCK:  Oh. You mean shot at it.</td></tr>

<tr id="L41"><td><a href="#L41">41</a></td><td>APPEL:  No. I mean shot it. With this. (a hand phaser)</td></tr>

<tr id="L42"><td><a href="#L42">42</a></td><td>SPOCK:  Fascinating.</td></tr>

<tr id="L43"><td><a href="#L43">43</a></td><td>APPEL:  A good, clean shot. Didn't even slow it down. Well, I've made my report to you. Production has stopped, nobody will go into the lower levels, and I don't blame them. If the Federation wants pergium, then you're going to have to do something about it.</td></tr>

<tr id="L44"><td><a href="#L44">44</a></td><td>KIRK:  That's why we're here, Mister Vanderberg.</td></tr>

<tr id="L45"><td><a href="#L45">45</a></td><td>APPEL:  You're all pretty tough, aren't you? Starship, phaser banks. You can't get your starship down in the tunnels.</td></tr>

<tr id="L46"><td><a href="#L46">46</a></td><td>KIRK:  I don't think we'll need to, Mister Appel. Mister Vanderberg, we'll need a complete subsurface chart of all the drifts, galleries and tunnels.</td></tr>

<tr id="L47"><td><a href="#L47">47</a></td><td>SOMEONE: Mister Vanderberg, I'll need a complete subsurface chart of all the drifts, galleries, tunnels.</td></tr>

<tr id="L48"><td><a href="#L48">48</a></td><td>VANDERBERG:  You'll get it.</td></tr>

<tr id="L49"><td><a href="#L49">49</a></td><td>SPOCK:  (examining a large globe from Vanderberg's desk) Mister Vanderberg, what is this?</td></tr>

<tr id="L50"><td><a href="#L50">50</a></td><td>VANDERBERG:  It's a silicon nodule. There are a millions of them are down there. No commercial value.</td></tr>

<tr id="L51"><td><a href="#L51">51</a></td><td>SPOCK:  But a geological oddity, to say the least. Pure silicon?</td></tr>

<tr id="L52"><td><a href="#L52">52</a></td><td>VANDERBERG:  A few trace elements. Look, we didn't call you here so you could collect rocks.</td></tr>

<tr id="L53"><td><a href="#L53">53</a></td><td>KIRK:  Thank you, Mister Vanderberg. We'll need your complete co-operation.</td></tr>

<tr id="L54"><td><a href="#L54">54</a></td><td>VANDERBERG:  You'll have it. Just find that creature, whatever it is. I've got a quota to meet. Come on, Appel.</td></tr>

<tr id="L55"><td><a href="#L55">55</a></td><td>ANNOTATION: They leave, and McCoy comes back.</td></tr>

<tr id="L56"><td><a href="#L56">56</a></td><td>KIRK:  The vast number of tunnels won't make our hunting any easier. Doc?</td></tr>

<tr id="L57"><td><a href="#L57">57</a></td><td>MCCOY:  Schmitter didn't burn to death, not in the usual sense, anyway.</td></tr>

<tr id="L58"><td><a href="#L58">58</a></td><td>KIRK:  Explain.</td></tr>

<tr id="L59"><td><a href="#L59">59</a></td><td>MCCOY:  Well, there are only fragments of bone and teeth left, but the plant's physician agrees with me. A chemical corrosion. Almost as if he'd been thrown into a vat of extremely corrosive acid.</td></tr>

<tr id="L60"><td><a href="#L60">60</a></td><td>KIRK:  Strong enough to eat machinery?</td></tr>

<tr id="L61"><td><a href="#L61">61</a></td><td>MCCOY:  Strong enough to eat anything else that you can think of.</td></tr>

<tr id="L62"><td><a href="#L62">62</a></td><td>KIRK:  Mister Spock.</td></tr>

<tr id="L63"><td><a href="#L63">63</a></td><td>SPOCK:  (at the mine map) I've charted the positions of the deaths and acts of sabotage. Here, here, and here. If the times of these incidents are to be accepted as accurate, the creature would have to have moved at an incredible rate of speed.</td></tr>

<tr id="L64"><td><a href="#L64">64</a></td><td>KIRK:  Mister Vanderberg, how recent are these charts?</td></tr>

<tr id="L65"><td><a href="#L65">65</a></td><td>VANDERBERG:  (reentering) They were made last year.</td></tr>

<tr id="L66"><td><a href="#L66">66</a></td><td>KIRK:  Before the appearance of whatever it is?</td></tr>

<tr id="L67"><td><a href="#L67">67</a></td><td>VANDERBERG:  That's right.</td></tr>

<tr id="L68"><td><a href="#L68">68</a></td><td>KIRK:  I see. Mister Spock give us a report on life beneath the surface.</td></tr>

<tr id="L69"><td><a href="#L69">69</a></td><td>SOMEONE: Within range of our sensors, there is no life, other than the accountable human residents of this colony beneath the surface. At least, no life as we know it.</td></tr>

<tr id="L70"><td><a href="#L70">70</a></td><td>KIRK:  We can't cover tunnel by tunnel on foot. We must get production going again. We must have that pergium.</td></tr>

<tr id="L71"><td><a href="#L71">71</a></td><td>SPOCK:  If we could force another appearance of this creature</td></tr>

<tr id="L72"><td><a href="#L72">72</a></td><td>VANDERBERG:  When that creature appears, men die.</td></tr>

<tr id="L73"><td><a href="#L73">73</a></td><td>ANNOTATION: And as if to prove his point, the guard outside the power plant is killed. There's just a vaguely man-shaped stain on the ground and wisps of smoke lead us to a neat circular hole in the door he was guarding.</td></tr>

<tr id="L74"><td><a href="#L74">74</a></td><td>KIRK:  Too many tunnels. We couldn't possibly. Mister Spock, our sensors can pick up normal life functions at a considerable distance, but what about abnormal life functions?</td></tr>

<tr id="L75"><td><a href="#L75">75</a></td><td>ANNOTATION: Just then the lights flicker and an alarm sounds.</td></tr>

<tr id="L76"><td><a href="#L76">76</a></td><td>VANDERBERG:  Something's happening in the reactor room!</td></tr>

<tr><td></td><td>LOCATION--Tunnel outside the reactor room</td></tr>
<tr id="L77"><td><a href="#L77">77</a></td><td>VANDERBERG:  Back to your stations. Look at that.</td></tr>

<tr id="L78"><td><a href="#L78">78</a></td><td>ANNOTATION: He goes through the hole cut in the door.</td></tr>

<tr id="L79"><td><a href="#L79">79</a></td><td>SPOCK:  I wouldn't touch it, Captain. An extremely active corrosive. Traces may linger.</td></tr>

<tr id="L80"><td><a href="#L80">80</a></td><td>VANDERBERG [OC]:  Kirk, quickly!</td></tr>

<tr><td></td><td>LOCATION--Reactor room</td></tr>
<tr id="L81"><td><a href="#L81">81</a></td><td>ANNOTATION: They step through carefully.</td></tr>

<tr id="L82"><td><a href="#L82">82</a></td><td>VANDERBERG:  The main circulating pump for the entire reactor is gone.</td></tr>

<tr id="L83"><td><a href="#L83">83</a></td><td>SPOCK:  The same indication as shown at the door, Captain. A very strong corrosive.</td></tr>

<tr id="L84"><td><a href="#L84">84</a></td><td>KIRK:  Is there a replacement for that?</td></tr>

<tr id="L85"><td><a href="#L85">85</a></td><td>VANDERBERG:  No, none. It's outdated, but we never had any trouble with it.</td></tr>

<tr id="L86"><td><a href="#L86">86</a></td><td>KIRK:  Spock, on board?</td></tr>

<tr id="L87"><td><a href="#L87">87</a></td><td>SPOCK:  Nothing for a device this antiquated, Captain.</td></tr>

<tr id="L88"><td><a href="#L88">88</a></td><td>VANDERBERG:  Without the pump mechanism, the reactor will go supercritical. It could poison half the planet. We can't shut it down. It provides heat and air and life support for the whole colony.</td></tr>

<tr id="L89"><td><a href="#L89">89</a></td><td>KIRK:  Mister Spock, we seem to have been given a choice. Death by asphyxiation or death by radiation poisoning.</td></tr>

<tr><td></td><td>LOCATION--Bridge</td></tr>
<tr id="L90"><td><a href="#L90">90</a></td><td>SCOTT:  A PXK pergium reactor? No, sir. We don't have any spare circulating pump for a thing like that. I haven't seen a PXK in twenty years.</td></tr>

<tr><td></td><td>LOCATION--Reactor room</td></tr>
<tr id="L91"><td><a href="#L91">91</a></td><td>KIRK:  Can you rig one up? It's vital.</td></tr>

<tr><td></td><td>LOCATION--Bridge</td></tr>
<tr id="L92"><td><a href="#L92">92</a></td><td>SCOTT:  Well sir, I can put together some odds and ends, but it won't hold for long.</td></tr>

<tr><td></td><td>LOCATION--Reactor room</td></tr>
<tr id="L93"><td><a href="#L93">93</a></td><td>KIRK:  How long?</td></tr>

<tr id="L94"><td><a href="#L94">94</a></td><td>SCOTT [OC]:  Forty eight hours maybe, with a bit of luck.</td></tr>

<tr id="L95"><td><a href="#L95">95</a></td><td>KIRK:  Forty eight hours is better than nothing. Gather what you need and beam down here with it.</td></tr>

<tr id="L96"><td><a href="#L96">96</a></td><td>SOMEONE: {Bridge]</td></tr>

<tr id="L97"><td><a href="#L97">97</a></td><td>KIRK [OC]:  Top priority.</td></tr>

<tr id="L98"><td><a href="#L98">98</a></td><td>SCOTT:  Aye, Captain.</td></tr>

<tr><td></td><td>LOCATION--Reactor room</td></tr>
<tr id="L99"><td><a href="#L99">99</a></td><td>SCOTT [OC]:  I'll be right down. Scott out.</td></tr>

<tr id="L100"><td><a href="#L100">100</a></td><td>VANDERBERG:  What happens when it breaks down?</td></tr>

<tr id="L101"><td><a href="#L101">101</a></td><td>KIRK:  Hopefully we'll have found the missing part by then.</td></tr>

<tr id="L102"><td><a href="#L102">102</a></td><td>VANDERBERG:  Hopefully. Small chance.</td></tr>

<tr id="L103"><td><a href="#L103">103</a></td><td>KIRK:  We'll have to, Chief. The alternative is to evacuate all you people up to the Enterprise. A dozen planets depend on you for pergium for their reactor. They're already screaming. Reactors closing down, life support systems</td></tr>

<tr id="L104"><td><a href="#L104">104</a></td><td>VANDERBERG:  I'm concerned with my people right here, Kirk. They're being murdered. You find that monster and kill it.</td></tr>

<tr><td></td><td>LOCATION--Vanderberg's office</td></tr>
<tr id="L105"><td><a href="#L105">105</a></td><td>SPOCK:  The missing pump wasn't taken by accident. It was the one piece of equipment absolutely essential for the operation of the reactor.</td></tr>

<tr id="L106"><td><a href="#L106">106</a></td><td>KIRK:  Do you think the creature is trying to push the colonists off the planet?</td></tr>

<tr id="L107"><td><a href="#L107">107</a></td><td>SPOCK:  It would seem so.</td></tr>

<tr id="L108"><td><a href="#L108">108</a></td><td>KIRK:  But why now, Mister Spock? These production facilities have been in operation for over fifty years.</td></tr>

<tr id="L109"><td><a href="#L109">109</a></td><td>SPOCK:  I don't know. But there is a possibility.</td></tr>

<tr id="L110"><td><a href="#L110">110</a></td><td>ANNOTATION: He goes over to the silicon nodule on the desk.</td></tr>

<tr id="L111"><td><a href="#L111">111</a></td><td>KIRK:  What's that?</td></tr>

<tr id="L112"><td><a href="#L112">112</a></td><td>SPOCK:  Life as we know it is universally based on some combination of carbon compounds, but what if life exists based on another element? For instance, silicon.</td></tr>

<tr id="L113"><td><a href="#L113">113</a></td><td>MCCOY:  You're creating fantasies, Mister Spock.</td></tr>

<tr id="L114"><td><a href="#L114">114</a></td><td>KIRK:  Not necessarily, Bones. I've heard of the theoretical possibility of life based on silicon. A silicon-based life would be of an entirely different order. It's possible that our phasers might not affect it.</td></tr>

<tr id="L115"><td><a href="#L115">115</a></td><td>SPOCK:  Certainly not phaser one, which is far less powerful than phaser two.</td></tr>

<tr id="L116"><td><a href="#L116">116</a></td><td>KIRK:  All right, how about this? A creature that lives deep in the planet below us, at home in solid rock. It seems to me that in order to survive, it would have to have some form of natural armour plating.</td></tr>

<tr id="L117"><td><a href="#L117">117</a></td><td>SPOCK:  It could explain much, especially since the colonists are armed only with phaser one.</td></tr>

<tr id="L118"><td><a href="#L118">118</a></td><td>KIRK:  But our people have phaser number two.</td></tr>

<tr id="L119"><td><a href="#L119">119</a></td><td>SPOCK:  Which I could adjust to be more effective against silicon.</td></tr>

<tr id="L120"><td><a href="#L120">120</a></td><td>MCCOY:  Silicon-based life is physiologically impossible, especially in an oxygen atmosphere.</td></tr>

<tr id="L121"><td><a href="#L121">121</a></td><td>SPOCK:  It may be, Doctor, that the creature can exist for brief periods in such an atmosphere before returning to its own environment.</td></tr>

<tr id="L122"><td><a href="#L122">122</a></td><td>MCCOY:  I still think you're imagining things.</td></tr>

<tr id="L123"><td><a href="#L123">123</a></td><td>KIRK:  You may be right, Doctor, but at least it's something to go on. Mister Spock, have Lieutenant Commander Giotto assemble the security troops and arm them with phaser number two. You make the proper adjustments. You seem fascinated by this rock.</td></tr>

<tr id="L124"><td><a href="#L124">124</a></td><td>SPOCK:  Yes, Captain. You recall that Vanderberg commented there were thousands of these at a lower level, the level which the machinery opened just prior to the first appearance of the creature.</td></tr>

<tr id="L125"><td><a href="#L125">125</a></td><td>KIRK:  Do they tie in?</td></tr>

<tr id="L126"><td><a href="#L126">126</a></td><td>SPOCK:  I don't know.</td></tr>

<tr id="L127"><td><a href="#L127">127</a></td><td>KIRK:  Speculate.</td></tr>

<tr id="L128"><td><a href="#L128">128</a></td><td>SPOCK:  I have already given Doctor McCoy sufficient cause for amusement. I'd prefer to cogitate the possibilities for a time.</td></tr>

<tr id="L129"><td><a href="#L129">129</a></td><td>KIRK:  A short time, Mister Spock. We have very little.</td></tr>

<tr><td></td><td>LOCATION--Reactor room</td></tr>
<tr id="L130"><td><a href="#L130">130</a></td><td>KIRK:  How's it going, Scotty?</td></tr>

<tr id="L131"><td><a href="#L131">131</a></td><td>SCOTT:  Well sir, it's a plumber's nightmare, but it'll hold for a bit.</td></tr>

<tr id="L132"><td><a href="#L132">132</a></td><td>KIRK:  It has to hold longer than a bit.</td></tr>

<tr id="L133"><td><a href="#L133">133</a></td><td>SCOTT:  Sorry, sir. That's about the best I can do, but I guarantee it's not good enough.</td></tr>

<tr id="L134"><td><a href="#L134">134</a></td><td>KIRK:  (answers comm. beep) Kirk here.</td></tr>

<tr id="L135"><td><a href="#L135">135</a></td><td>SPOCK [OC]:  Captain, the security officers have gathered in Chief Vanderberg's office.</td></tr>

<tr id="L136"><td><a href="#L136">136</a></td><td>KIRK:  I'll be right there. Kirk out. Scotty, ride herd on it. Kind words. Tender, loving care. Kiss it. Baby it. Flatter it if you have to, but keep it going.</td></tr>

<tr id="L137"><td><a href="#L137">137</a></td><td>SCOTT:  I'll do what I can, sir.</td></tr>

<tr><td></td><td>LOCATION--Vanderberg's office</td></tr>
<tr id="L138"><td><a href="#L138">138</a></td><td>ANNOTATION: Six red-shirted men are lined up.</td></tr>

<tr id="L139"><td><a href="#L139">139</a></td><td>KIRK:  You will proceed from level to level, checking out every foot, every opening. You are searching for some sort of creature which is highly resistant to phaser fire. Phasers will be set on maximum, and remember this. Fifty people have died. I want no more deaths.</td></tr>

<tr id="L140"><td><a href="#L140">140</a></td><td>VANDERBERG:  Except the bloody thing.</td></tr>

<tr id="L141"><td><a href="#L141">141</a></td><td>KIRK:  The creature may or may not attack on sight. However, you must. It is vitally important we get this installation back into production.</td></tr>

<tr id="L142"><td><a href="#L142">142</a></td><td>SPOCK:  Mister Vanderberg, may I ask at which level you discovered the nodules of silicon?</td></tr>

<tr id="L143"><td><a href="#L143">143</a></td><td>VANDERBERG:  The twenty-third. Why?</td></tr>

<tr id="L144"><td><a href="#L144">144</a></td><td>SOMEONE: Commander Giotto, take your detail. Go directly to the twenty-third level. Start your search there.</td></tr>

<tr id="L145"><td><a href="#L145">145</a></td><td>GIOTTO:  Aye, aye, sir. May I ask if you have reason to suspect this creature may be on that level?</td></tr>

<tr id="L146"><td><a href="#L146">146</a></td><td>KIRK:  It's one of the possibilities we've discussed. (to Vanderberg) I want your people to stay on the top level, together at a safe place.</td></tr>

<tr id="L147"><td><a href="#L147">147</a></td><td>VANDERBERG:  I don't know any safe place, Captain, the way that thing comes and goes.</td></tr>

<tr id="L148"><td><a href="#L148">148</a></td><td>KIRK:  Well, gentlemen, you have your instructions. Let's get at it.</td></tr>

